This paper is likely to belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category as it describes the creation of a corpus of speech utterances and the development of an automatic speech recognition system. It may also belong to the Sound and Music Computing (cs.SD) sub-category as it deals with speech recordings. Additionally, the paper may be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories as it involves the use of human experts to score the utterances and the development of an automatic assessment system. Finally, the paper may be relevant to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category as it involves the assessment of language proficiency in students.
